In a small #pot, combine @Basmati Rice{1/2%cup}, @water{3/4%cup}, and a pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to use in Step 6.

Meanwhile, wash and dry produce. Halve, peel, and finely chop @onion{1}(finely chopped). Trim @Green Beans{6%ounce} if necessary; halve crosswise.

Rinse @Shrimp{10%ounce} under cold water, then pat dry with #paper towels. Season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a large drizzle of @Cooking Oil{2%teaspoon} in a large #pan over medium-high heat. Once pan is hot, add half the @Ground Cumin{1%teaspoon}, half the @Curry Powder{1%tablespoon}, and half the @Garam Masala{1%teaspoon}. Cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

> For 4 servings, use all the cumin, all the curry powder, and all the garam masala.

To pan with spices, add onion, @Garlic Powder{1%teaspoon}, @Butter{1%tablespoon}, @Sugar{1/8%tsp}, and a large pinch of salt. Cook, stirring occasionally, until onion is softened and lightly browned, ~{3-5%minutes}.

> For 4 servings, use 2 TBSP butter and 1/4 tsp sugar.

Add green beans, shrimp, and @water{1/2%cup}. Cook, stirring, until liquid has reduced and shrimp are opaque and cooked through, ~{3-4%minutes}.

> If mixture seems dry before shrimp are done, stir in a splash of water. If there is still water remaining, continue to cook until reduced. Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Meanwhile, roughly chop @Cilantro{1/4%ounce}.

Fluff rice with a #fork; season with salt and pepper to taste.

Divide rice between #shallow bowls{}; top with shrimp and green beans. Garnish with cilantro and serve.